The first stack will be used to hold the front of the queue, and the second stack will be used to hold the back of the queue. Each time an item is enqueued, its position in the queue will be updated in the front stack, while its position in the back stack will remain the same. Similarly, when an item is dequeued, its position in the front stack will remain the same while its position in the back stack will be updated.

Here is the implementation of a queue using two stacks:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.front = []
        self.back = []
    def enqueue(self, item):
        if not self.front:
            self.front.append(item)
        else:
            self.back.append(item)
        self.front = self.front[1:] + [item]
    def dequeue(self):
        if not self.front:
            return None
        else:
            return self.front.pop()

    def size(self):
